i‚Äôm in the midst of learning more about the post-work movement ‚Äî which seeks to understand why we continue to subscribe to capitalist systems that fail us and explores what a ‚Äúpost-work‚Äù future might look like ‚Äî and i found this book to be a deeply compelling example of the need for a workplace and work systems revolution
.
geissler, a freelance writer who finds herself in need of some extra income, writes in a sort of split narrative style where she‚Äôs speaking to ‚Äúyou‚Äù as if you‚Äôve taken on the warehouse job after she‚Äôs left. it allows her to insert commentary on what she wishes she‚Äôd done differently ‚Äî how she wishes she‚Äôd reacted to different demoralizing situations throughout her time at the warehouse
.
SEASONAL ASSOCIATE exposes many of the ways that low-wage work infantilizes and subjugates workers, such as having to get a sick note to take leave like you‚Äôre still a child in school. i found this entire story utterly maddening, and it‚Äôs reinforced my belief that our current work systems are irreparably broken. i‚Äôm very interested in learning more about post-work as a concept and exploring ways i can productively contribute to fixing these failed systems
.
